Q: Workarounds for using __has_include when it may or may not be defined - Is it valid to pass __has_include as a macro argument? A: <p>You could abstract the <code>__has_include</code> logic into a generic wrapper header:</p>
<pre><code>/* wrap-boiler-plate.h */
/* NB: No pragma once, since this file is generic */
#ifdef __has_include
  #if __has_include(MY_HEADER)
    #include MY_HEADER
    #define HAS_INCLUDE_HEADER_H
  #endif
#endif

#ifndef HAS_INCLUDE_HEADER_H
  #include MY_BACKUP_HEADER
#endif

#undef HAS_INCLUDE_HEADER_H

#undef MY_HEADER
#undef MY_BACKUP_HEADER
</code></pre>
<p>Then, you have a wrapper header file instance that uses the generic one:</p>
<pre><code>/* wrapped-header.h */
#pragma once
#define MY_HEADER &lt;header.h&gt;
#define MY_BACKUP_HEADER &quot;backup-header.h&quot;
#include &quot;wrap-boiler-plate.h&quot;
</code></pre>

Q: Take in multiple numeric inputs and sum in javascript automatically when input is changed A: <p>Your code is pretty close to achieving what you need, you've just made a slight mistake: you've put the <em>listener</em> on the wrong element (<strong>findiv</strong>), when you should have put it on the elements you expect to change, those belonging to the <strong>.fin</strong> class.</p>
